A binary string is monotone increasing if it consists of some number of 0's (possibly none), followed by some number of 1's (also possibly none).

You are given a binary string s. You can flip s[i] changing it from 0 to 1 or from 1 to 0.

Return the minimum number of flips to make s monotone increasing.

class Solution {
    public int minFlipsMonoIncr(String s) {
        int len = s.length();
        //prefix contains how many 1's on the left side of current node
        //suffix contains number of 0's on the right side of current position
        int[] prefix = new int[len];
        int[] suffix = new int[len];
        prefix[0] = s.charAt(0)=='1'? 1:0;
        suffix[len-1] = s.charAt(len-1)=='0'? 1:0;
        for(int i=1,j=len-2; i<len; i++,j--){
            prefix[i] = prefix[i-1] + (s.charAt(i)=='1'? 1:0);
            suffix[j] = suffix[j+1] + (s.charAt(j)=='0'? 1:0);
        }
        //number of flipping we need is prefix+suffix
        int minimum = Integer.MAX_VALUE;
        for(int i=-1; i<=len-1; i++){
            int left = (i==-1)? 0:prefix[i];
            int right = (i==len-1)? 0:suffix[i+1];
            minimum = Math.min(minimum, left+right);
        }
        
        return minimum;
    }
}
